<%= faq_schema([
  { question: "How does JSON to CSV conversion work?", answer: "The converter parses a JSON array of objects and extracts all unique keys from every object to form the CSV header row. It then iterates over each object, outputting the value for each header key as a CSV field. If an object is missing a key, an empty value is inserted. This approach handles heterogeneous data where objects may have different sets of keys, using the union of all keys as the column set." },
  { question: "What JSON structure is required for conversion?", answer: "The input must be a JSON array of objects, such as [{\"name\":\"Alice\",\"age\":30},{\"name\":\"Bob\",\"age\":25}]. The array cannot be empty, and every element must be a JSON object (not a string, number, or nested array). Nested objects and arrays within the objects are converted to their string representation in the CSV output. For deeply nested JSON, consider flattening the structure before conversion." },
  { question: "How are missing values handled?", answer: "When objects in the JSON array have different sets of keys, the converter uses the union of all keys as the header row. For any object that lacks a particular key, the corresponding CSV field is left empty. This produces a complete rectangular table where every row has the same number of columns, even if the source data is sparse. Null values are also represented as empty CSV fields." },
  { question: "Which delimiter should I choose?", answer: "Comma is the standard CSV delimiter and works with virtually all spreadsheet applications and data tools. Use tab if you are creating a TSV file for import into databases or scientific tools. Semicolons are standard in European locales where the comma serves as the decimal separator. Pipe delimiters are used in some enterprise and financial data systems where commas and semicolons may appear in field values." },
  { question: "How are special characters in values handled?", answer: "Values that contain the delimiter character, double quotes, or newlines are automatically wrapped in double quotes following the CSV standard (RFC 4180). Double quotes within values are escaped by doubling them. This ensures that the output can be parsed correctly by any standards-compliant CSV reader. Numeric values and booleans from the JSON are converted to their string representation in the CSV." }
]) %>

